[[File:Sugar city 5.jpg|thumb|The first of a series of gablestones on a [[Gemeenlandshuis]] in [[Halfweg]] built in 1645; each stone represents the heraldic shield of the dike-reeve and his men, known as the ''[[heemraden]]'', or in this case, the high or ''hoogheemraden'']] A '''dijkgraaf''' (translated: ''dike-warden'' or ''dike-reeve''), sometimes called a '''watergraaf''', is the [[chair (official)|chair]] of a [[Politics of the Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Water board (The Netherlands)|water board]]. He is the equivalent of a [[mayor]] in local government and a [[King's Commissioner]] in provincial government, chairing both the legislative and executive council, while having both ceremonial and representational roles as well as his own portfolios. The term goes back to pre-medieval days.
Literally the term means "[[Dike (construction)|Dike]] [[count]]", like other titles ending in ''-graaf'' (equivalent to English -grave and German ''-[[graf]]'') of feudal origin, but remained a functional official. The government bodies in the Netherlands today in order of rank are: #National #Provincial #Municipal #Water boards.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} In medieval times and earlier however, the water boards were the same as municipal, and since it was a country of duchies, the Water board (''Waterschap'') was in governmental terms the equivalent of a city (''Stad''), and thus also the highest form of government.
==References== * [http://gtb.inl.nl/iWDB/search?actie=article&wdb=MNW&id=06655&lemmodern=dijkgraaf Dijkgraaf] definition (Dutch) * [http://watercanon.nederlandleeftmetwater.nl/view/canon/waterboard Water Canon]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (English version) website of The [[Ministry of Transport, Public Works and Water Management]] {{Dutch decentral government}}
