[[File:Seme.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.5|Sketch of a seme]]A '''seme''',<ref>[http://www.connectingcultures.us/resources/artifacts/art_item.php?accno1=COST&accno2=KEN&accno3=531 "Kenyan Maasai "Ol Alem" "], connectingcultures.us</ref><ref>[http://www.vikingsword.com/lew/w0023/w0023.html "African Masai Seme (Ol Alem)"], Lew Waldman's Ethnographic Arms & Armour</ref> '''simi'''<ref name=simi/> or '''ol alem'''<ref>[http://www.higgins-collection.org/artifacts/1618 "Ol alem (sword)"], John Woodman Higgins Armory collection</ref> is a type of [[dagger]] or short [[sword]] used by the [[Maasai people|Maasai]] and [[Kikuyu people]]s of Kenya in East Africa.<ref name=simi>[http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30001263 "Kikuyu simi with scabbard"], IWM</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A Glossary of the Construction, Decoration, and Use of Arms and Armor in All Countries and in All Times: In All Countries and in All Times |last=Stone |first=George Cameron |authorlink= George Cameron Stone|author2=LaRocca, Donald J.  |year=1999 |publisher=Dover Publications |location= |isbn=978-0-486-40726-5 |page=547 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A4Rp_Qx9in4C |accessdate=2008-12-29 }}</ref>
They have a distinctive leaf-shaped blade, with a relatively rounded point. [[Scabbard]]s are generally made of wood covered with rawhide, and dyed red.

